Z.Q. Wu &amp; C.L. Zhao.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="86" pageId="4" pageNumber="85" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="85">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Meruliaceae" genus="Elaphroporia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Elaphroporia" order="Polyporales" pageId="4" pageNumber="85" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">Elaphroporia</taxonomicName>
(Lat.): referring to the basidiocarps light-weight upon drying.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="5" pageNumber="86">
<pageBreakToken pageId="5" pageNumber="86" start="start">Basidiocarps</pageBreakToken>
annual, resupinate, becoming rigid and light-weight up on drying. Pore surface cream to pale yellow when fresh, turning to yellow upon drying. Hyphal system monomitic; generative hyphae thick-walled bearing both clamp connections and simple septa, slightly amyloid, CB+. Basidiospores ellipsoid, hyaline, thin-walled, smooth, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="IKI–">IKI-</normalizedToken>
, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="CB–">CB-</normalizedToken>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
